{[%evp 0,27,16,10,15,-1,24,22,40,23,26,-7,-4,16,4,4,16,6,20,1,13,12,3,-18,34,
28,26,-2,-5,-12]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 {In my first database, I
have split the work between the solid positions of the Exchange Variation and
less popular but interesting lines for White on move 4. We have also examined
two options against 3.Nc3. Now it is time to understand why the most popular
lines offer better chances of fighting for advantage for White.} (4. Nbd2 $5 {
is another rare line that is also analyzed in this database. It is important
to cover this move both because of its potentially dangerous surprise value as
well as because the structures and ideas are fairly similar to the ones we
discuss later in the main chapters devoted to 4.e3 Bf5.}) ({We have almost
half of this database dedicated to analyse} 4. e3 {which I think can be called
the modern main line, where White has the best shot at obtaining the opening
advantage.} Bf5 5. Nc3 ({In Chapter 2 I analyze White's sidelines. Most of
them don't pose any theoretical problems for Black, yet it is vital to cover
those possibilities.} 5. cxd5 $5 {is a worthy try that was played by some
strong grandmasters. It is helpful to analyze such variations in order to
understand our main ideas and how Black can obtain an excellent position when
the opponent does not play in the most ambitious manner possible.}) 5... e6 6.
Nh4 {[%csl Gf5] This is the point: White allows Black to develop the
light-squared bishop as he hopes to later trap and exchange it, obtaining the
bishop pair. As a result, a very complicated position arises, where even very
subtle differences in the pawn structure can shift the evaluation drastically.
My recommendation now is to try to make White's task more complicated with} Be4
$5 7. f3 Bg6 {[%csl Gf3] when the inclusion of the move f2-f3 considerably
changes the position and makes White's structure a bit loose.  I don't want to
give you any spoiler, but this line leads to a vivid middlegame where both
sides enjoy interesting positions and fighting chances. This position is so
rich in possibilities that I have dedicated three chapters to it.  Chapter 3
deals with positional lines where White castles short and hopes to eventually
exploit his main long-term asset, namely the bishop pair.  In Chapter 4, we
discuss positions where White goes for sharp play by castling long, trying to
take advantage of 7.f3 by either planning operations in the center or
launching a kingside attack. Finally, in Chapter 5, I've checked some other
interesting ideas. Of course, in all those lines Black has his own plans and
counter chances.}) 4... dxc4 {In the second half of this database I analyse
this very classical position.} 5. a4 (5. e3 {Is a solid option that sidesteps
the main lines and allows White to cut on the theoretical learning. However,
of course, this does not present any theoretical challenges to Black. This
variation and other sidelines on move 5 are analysed on Chapter 6.} b5) ({
In Chapter 7 I show how Black can neutralize the dangerous Geller Gambit:} 5.
e4 $5 b5 {This position used to be considered safe for Black, but thanks to
new discoveries of the highly creative Russian GM Daniil Dubov, this variation
has enjoyed a fresh spark of popularity as finding the path to safety took
Black a few painful losses. However, now it's well-known that as long as Black
knows a few right ideas, he is doing great, and of course, I am showing those
ideas to you!}) 5... Bf5 6. e3 (6. Nh4 $5 {might seem a bit hasty now as Black
has not played e7-e6 yet. Still, it is an interesting way to continue that
avoids main theory and is being used once in a while even by strong GMs. I
think Black has at least two solid ways to face this line.  Both of them are
analysed on Chapter 8.}) 6... e6 7. Bxc4 Bb4 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe2 {Historically,
this has been Slav's classic main line.} (9. Qb3 {Is possible, although it can
hardly offer chances for the opening advantage. This move, just as other
sidelines, is analysed in Chapter 9.}) (9. Nh4 $5 {makes more sense here, as
Black has already played e7-e6 and can't save the bishop. White could claim
that this is an improved version of the 4.e3 variation as the centre is more
flexible, but things are not that simple. Black now has a choice between solid
and fighting continuations. To me it seems that both lead to good positions!})
9... Nbd7 10. e4 Bg6 11. Bd3 Bh5 $1 {[%cal Ge6e5] White can't keep the centre
flexible now due to the threat of e6-e5.} 12. e5 Nd5 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Qe3 {
And we have the classic main position. After the exchange of knights on d5, we
have the typical French structure where the typically bad c8-bishop has
managed to get outside of the pawn chain. That's great news for us! Still,
White has a bit more space and can try to fight for the advantage in two
different ways: by trying to build an attack on the kingside or by exploiting
the space advantage in the long run, which often implies simplifications.
Black has to be aware of how to face both plans, but in general his position
is very solid and can always be defended with correct play. Both plans are
examined in details on Chapter 10.} *

