{[%evp 0,34,25,32,32,-16,24,24,24,10,38,1,47,53,27,51,70,28,54,-30,51,19,-6,13,
36,-2,-24,-60,-73,-7,-27,-27,-10,-10,7,-29,-14]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6
4. Nbd2 $5 {I have decided to devote the first chapter to this tricky sideline.
It is quite harmless if Black is aware of a few ideas, yet it's important to
cover it in order to avoid some nasty pitfalls. The reason why I am analyzing
it here, and not in the first part of the Slav repertoire where I was
discussing other sidelines on move 4, is because the arising positions are
very similar to the ones after 4.e3.} Bf5 5. Nh4 {The same idea as in the
variation with 4.e3: White wants to grab the bishop pair.} (5. Qb3 {was tried
in a few games, but I don't think it can pose serious problems for Black.} Qc7
{White has different possibilities at this point, but in any case, Black gets
a comfortable game.} (5... Qb6 {Is another option, likely transposing to
positions similar to the ones discussed elsewhere in the repertoire.}) 6. g3 (
6. e3 h6 $1 {Now that Nh4 is no longer an idea, Black is extremely comfortable.
}) (6. Nh4 $6 {As we will see, the combination of the moves Nh4 and Qb3 works
better when White starts with the knight move. In the present case Black has
extra options like} Be6 $5 {[%csl Yb3,Yh4] when both the queen and the knight
seem a bit misplaced. Black is doing well after something like} 7. e3 dxc4 8.
Bxc4 Bxc4 9. Nxc4 e6 $11 {followed by normal development and either e6-e5 or
c6-c5, equalizing.}) 6... h6 $1 {[%csl Gh7] This position is very similar to
those analysed in the first database on the 4.g3 variation. Like in that line 
(and in general, more or less), you should play this move if given the chance,
in order to preserve the light-squared bishop on the h7-b1 diagonal.} 7. Bg2 e6
8. O-O Nbd7 {Black is fine, as we can see in two illustrative games:} 9. Re1 (
9. a3 Be7 10. Qc3 O-O 11. b4 a5 12. c5 b6 13. Bb2 {Hoang,T (2410)-Kulkarni,V 
(2161) Hanoi HD Bank op-A 8th 2018 (4) 1/2} {Black's position resembles some
lines of the Orthodox, except by the fact that the bishop standing on f5 (it
normally is on either b7 or a6) is a big improvement. Since the b1-square is
taken from the White rooks, a nice plan would be} Rfb8 $15 {[%cal Yc7b7,Gb6c5]
followed by increasing the pressure along the b-file and waiting the right
moment to open lines with bxc5.}) 9... Be7 10. Qc3 a5 $1 11. a3 a4 $1 {White
has prevented the annoying threat of Bb4, but allowed Black to restrict his
queenside.} 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Ne5 O-O 14. f3 {White tried to advance in the
centre now, but after the typical reaction:} c5 $1 {he had problems holding on
to his center.} 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. dxc5 d4 17. Qc4 Rfc8 $36 {Singh,D (2132)
-Raghunandan,K (2410) Mumbai Mayors Cup 10th 2017 (9) 0-1 and Black had strong
initiative.}) 5... Be4 $1 {This move, which makes sense in the 4.e3 lines, is
even better here.} ({After} 5... Bg6 6. Qb3 {Black should be careful to avoid
falling into the only trap in this line:} Qb6 $2 (6... Qc7 {is the right move,
but after} 7. Nxg6 hxg6 8. g3 {[%cal Yf1g2,Ge2e4] I feel somehow White was
successful in the opening, as he managed to get the bishop pair and keep a
nice flexible position.}) 7. Qh3 $1 {[%cal Gh3c8,Yh4g6] The queen suddenly
creates a lot of threats and Black should accept an inferior structure after
the subsequent exchange on g6, which would be a nearly lost position for us.})
6. f3 {The most popular move. White can try to fight for an advantage with
less committal moves as well.} (6. Nxe4 Nxe4 {[%csl Yh4][%cal Ge7e5] Usually,
White should try to exchange the other knight for the bishop, as it is already
misplaced on h4. Black is already threatening e7-e5 now, so} 7. Nf3 {looks
sensible, but Black can still try} e5 $5 {[%cal Yf8b4] to get an active game.}
({After the more solid} 7... e6 8. a3 Nd7 9. e3 Bd6 {Black is also fine. He is
basically playing a Stonewall without his worst piece, the light-squared
bishop.} 10. Bd3 f5 11. O-O O-O 12. b4 Qf6 13. Bb2 g5 $5 {Ipatov,A (2650)
-Robson,R (2653) Saint Louis Fall-A 2019 (3) 0-1 with mutual chances.}) 8. a3
$8 ({After both} 8. dxe5 $2 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Qb6 $1 10. e3 Nd7 $17) ({and} 8. cxd5
$2 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Nxd2 10. Nxd2 exd4 $17 {Black is already much better.}) 8...
exd4 9. Qxd4 Bc5 $1 10. Qe5+ $2 ({White should forget about f2 and take the
risks by means of} 10. Qxg7 $1 Bxf2+ 11. Kd1 Rf8 {[%csl Rd1] when the White
king looks more vulnerable on d1, but White should be able to keep the balance
with} 12. Qe5+ $1 Qe7 $13) 10... Kf8 11. e3 Nd7 {White has managed to defend
f2, but the exposed position of his queen becomes an issue now.} 12. Qf5 {
Reich,T (2349)-De Visser,L (2258) AUT-chT2W 1617 2016 (10.3) 1-0} {After
something like} g6 13. Qf4 h5 $1 $17 {[%cal Yc5d6,Gf8g7] White is clearly
under pressure.}) ({White can try} 6. Qb3 {His hope is to put pressure on b7
and grab the e4-bishop somewhat later. Still, Black has at least two playable
options:} Nbd7 $5 {This is the active way. Black offers the b7-pawn for quick
development} (6... Qb6 {This is the solid way.} 7. f3 {Black can make White's
plan now more difficult by means of} (7. Nxe4 Nxe4 8. Qxb6 axb6 {Black
basically has no problems after the exchanges.} 9. e3 ({Comparing this
position with the notes of Black's 7th move,} 9. cxd5 e6 $1 {[%cal Gf8b4,Ye6d5]
is an important intermediate move, Black will play exd5 and keep a healthy
structure.}) 9... e6 10. Bd3 Nd7 11. Nf3 Be7 12. Ke2 O-O 13. Bd2 Nd6 14. cxd5
exd5 $11 {Krishna,C (2390)-Postny,E (2620) Sitges Sunway op 2016 (8) 0-1 The
position is of course balanced, but Black displayed great technique to win the
endgame.}) (7. e3 {this is harmless for Black.} e6 8. Be2 (8. Nxe4 dxe4 $1 {
[%cal Yg7g5,Gf8b4] might be a bit unpleasant for White.}) 8... Qxb3 $1 {
A simple path to equalize.} 9. Nxb3 (9. axb3 c5 $1 {[%cal Yb8c6] seems also
fine for Black.}) 9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 Bd5 ({The computer suggests an ambitious
line:} 10... g5 $1 11. Nf3 g4 12. Nh4 Nbd7 {[%csl Gh4] and White can have some
problems with the knight on the edge.}) 11. Nd2 c5 12. dxc5 Bxc5 $11 {Nabaty,T
(2688)-Svane,R (2599) Moscow Aeroflot op-A 18th 2019 (5) 1/2}) 7... Qxb3 $1 8.
Nxb3 (8. axb3 {was played once, but the pawn is a target now.} Bc2 $1 {[%csl
Gc2][%cal Yg7g5] This bishop is really annoying on c2.} 9. g4 e6 10. c5 {
Svane,R (2560)-Fontaine,R (2549) PRO League Central rapid 2017 (4) 0-1} {
A nice continuation now would be} Na6 $1 {[%cal Ya6b4]} 11. Ra4 Be7 12. Ng2 e5
$1 13. e3 Nc7 $15 {White is unable to get rid of the doubled pawns by means of
