[Annotator "IM Renato Quintiliano"]
[PlyCount "42"]
[SourceVersionDate "2020.04.08"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 {This is the only way
to fight for an advantage in the 4.e3 Variation. White allows the
light-squared bishop to be developed in front of the pawn chain just to
exchange it for the knight, trying to exlploit this imbalance later.} Be4 $5 {
All bishop moves are playable, but I think this seems the most fighting option
for me} (6... Bg4 {and}) (6... Bg6 {are possibly more solid.}) 7. f3 (7. Nxe4
$2 dxe4 $1 8. g3 c5 {[%cal Gb8c6] is already pleasant for Black.}) 7... Bg6 {
[%csl Gf3] Why did Black force the advance f2-f3?  It may look like a loss of
time because the bishop can still be exchanged with Nxg6. However, in such
positional lines any pawn move may cause relevant changes in the position.
Black expects to exploit the vulnerability of the diagonals b8-h2 and h4-e1.
Besides that, the e3-pawn might be a weakness as well. In the next variations,
we will see some examples how White's position can suddenly start looking
suspicious from the strategic viewpoint.} 8. Qb3 {[%csl Ye1][%cal Ye1g1] White
