c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 $5 {This ambitious move is called The
Geller Gambit, as the strong Soviet grandmaster has played it with success in
many games in the past. White sacrifices the pawn but in return gets a strong
centre and chances to seize initiative on the kingside in the middlegame. This
line was kind of forgotten in grandmaster practice until the creative Russian
GM Daniil Dubov brought a new spark of life in it lately.} b5 6. e5 {The
classic main line and most aggressive option.} (6. Be2 $5 {can be considered
the modern main line. White keeps the position flexible and aims to exploit
the compensation in a positional way. This is a logical approach, since both
tournament practice and computer preparation have proven that Black's
defensive resources are sufficient if White tries the more aggressive plans.
This move has gained a lot of popularity in the last couple of years and
became the favourite attempt of many GMs to get an advantage so we should take
it seriously.} e6 ({After} 6... b4 $6 7. Na4 Nxe4 8. Bxc4 $44 {White has
enough compensation due to the open e and c-files for the rooks and because
his knight is coming to c5. Recent games prove this evaluation.}) 7. O-O ({
The problem with} 7. a4 $2 b4 $1 {is that the a4-square is not available for
the knight anymore. One blitz game even went} 8. e5 $2 {which is simply bad
for White.} bxc3 9. exf6 cxb2 10. fxg7 bxa1=Q 11. gxh8=Q Qa5+ 12. Kf1 {Halkias,
S (2553)-Heinemann,J (2255) Riga Tal Memorial blitz 2019 (5) 1/2} {Now, after}
Q5c3 $1 13. Bh6 Nd7 {White is basically lost.} 14. Qxh7 Bxh6 15. Qxh6 Rb8 $19 {
[%cal Yb8b1]}) 7... Bb7 8. b3 $5 {This is clearly the most critical attempt
for White.} (8. Bg5 {Is the most frequent move, but after} Nbd7 9. e5 h6 10.
Bh4 g5 11. Bg3 {the game has transposed to a dubious line for White in the
Anti-Moscow Variation. The reason is that White loses many ideas after
advancing e4-e5, like Ne5 or a timely d4-d5 breakthrough.} Nh5 $1 {This is
better than Nd5 as Black can grab the bishop pair and the exchange on d5 would
prevent the freeing advance c6-c5.} 12. a4 a6 13. Qc2 Qb6 14. Rfd1 Be7 15. Ne4
{Valgmae,T (2226)-Fridman,D (2639) Liepajas Rokade op rapid 2014 (10) 0-1} {
Black could prepare to break in the centre with c6-c5 now:} Rd8 $1 16. b3 $5 {
